              <a href="/us/blog/all-about-sex/202404/the-bad-news-about-teen-sex-education-reflects-good-trends"><img loading="lazy" src="https://cdn2.psychologytoday.com/assets/styles/manual_crop_1_1_288x288/public/teaser_image/blog_entry/2024-04/sex-education-7188989_1280.jpg?itok=5XoQFfsM" width="288" height="288" alt="" title="viarami / Pixabay" />

</a>

      
      </div>
    
    <div class="teaser-lg__details">
      
                        <div class="h2 teaser-lg__title">
            <a href="/us/blog/all-about-sex/202404/the-bad-news-about-teen-sex-education-reflects-good-trends" rel="bookmark">The Bad News About Teen Sex Education Reflects Good Trends</a>
          </div>
              
      
              <p class="teaser-lg__summary teaser-lg__teaser--desktop">
            School-based teen sex education has declined 20 percent over the past 24 years. That sounds bad. But it reflects two good trends: fewer teen pregnancies and less HIV/AIDS.
      </p>
          </div>

  </div>

      <p class="teaser-lg__summary teaser-lg__teaser--mobile">
            School-based teen sex education has declined 20 percent over the past 24 years. That sounds bad. But it reflects two good trends: fewer teen pregnancies and less HIV/AIDS.
      </p>
  </article>
</div>
